gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G002428/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&amp;quot;Multiculturalism&amp;quot; has faced increasing criticism in recent years, both within popular opinion and academic debates, ranging from fears that it encourages the segregation of communities and helps create grounds for Islamic extremism, to claims that it undermines human rights, in particular that it can reinforce the oppression of women. Against this background, the central aims of the research are a) to explore the compatibility of policies of multiculturalism with fostering conditions for greater cross-cultural understanding and community cohesion; and b) to investigate the relation of multicultural policies and equality within cultures, focusing on tensions between cultural diversity and gender equality.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />The postdoctoral fellowship extends doctoral research which investigated the experiences of Muslims living in Britain and argued that a form of multicultural integration is necessary for achieving greater cross-cultural understanding and interaction. Drawing on Hans Georg Gadamer's philosophical hermeneutics and the feminist ?world travelling approach? for its theoretical framework, it explored a form of multiculturalism which emphasized the dynamic and fluid nature of culture and identity and the importance of human agency. The fellowship seeks to develop these themes through qualitative research with British Muslim women and to disseminate the outputs to policy makers and practitioners as well as academics.
